04407nam a2200625Ia 9781846156243DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20082008xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461562437 a10.1515/97818461562432doi  a(DE-B1597)677190  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a940.1/82qOCoLC222/eng/20230216  aNM 76502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/126432:1 aPurkis, William J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrusading Spirituality in the Holy Land and Iberia, c.1095-c.1187 /cWilliam J. Purkis. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (228 p.) :b1 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Abbreviations -- tMap of Western Europe, the Mediterranean and the Latin East (c.1145) -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Monastic Response to the First Crusade -- t2. The Foundations of Crusading Spirituality, 1095–c.1110 -- t3. Pilgrimage, Mimesis and the Holy Land, 1099–c.1149 -- t4. The Cistercian Influence on Crusading Spirituality, c.1128–1187 -- t5. The Introduction of Crusading to Iberia, 1096–c.1134 -- t6. The Development of Crusading Spirituality in Iberia, c.1130–c.1150 -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArgues for a new context for the origins and development of crusading, as an imitation of Christ.For much of the twelfth century the ideals and activities of crusaders were often described in language more normally associated with a monastic rather than a military vocation; like those who took religious vows, crusaders were repeatedly depicted as being driven by a desire to imitate Christ and to live according to the values of the primitive Church. This book argues that the significance of these descriptions has yet to be fully appreciated, and suggests that the origins and early development of crusading should be studied within the context of the "reformation" of professed religious life in the twelfth century, whose leading figures (such as St Bernard of Clairvaux) advocated the pursuit of devotional undertakings that were modelled on the lives of Christ and his apostles. It also considers topics such as the importance of pilgrimage to early crusading ideology and the relationship between the spirituality of crusading and the activities of the Military Orders, offering a revisionist assessment of how crusading ideas adapted and evolved when introduced to the Iberian peninsula in c.1120. In so doing, the book situates crusading within a broader context of changes in the religious culture of the medieval West. Dr WILLIAM PURKIS is Senior Lecturer in Medieval History at the University of Birmingham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHispanic Studies. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCrusading.  aHoly Land.  aIberia.  aImitation of Christ.  aMedieval Europe.  aMedieval history.  aMedieval spirituality.  aMilitary Orders.  aReligious culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615624340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156243/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles